name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 15. Never assume that the person you are talking to isn‚Äôt autistic, just because they don‚Äôt appear to be. Time and time again I‚Äôve been involved in conversations where people just assume that I‚Äôm not autistic, because how could I be? This is exhausting. Never make assumptions.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 14. Meltdowns aren‚Äôt the same thing as tantrums. Meltdowns are involuntary responses to feeling overwhelmed. Stop labelling autistic kids ‚Äúnaughty‚Äù or ‚Äúspoilt‚Äù for something that they can‚Äôt control. Support them and try to understand the trigger instead.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 13. We are fed up of people who aren‚Äôt autistic having conversations about us without us. We deserve to be involved in discussions about us without being shut out. In fact, we must be involved. You must consult us. Autism training is not training without autistic trainers.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 12. Everyone is not on the spectrum. The spectrum means each autistic person experiences different combinations of traits to diff intensities. Just because you share a trait (because, spoiler, we are human, so autistic traits are human traits), doesn‚Äôt mean you‚Äôre autistic.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: You wouldn‚Äôt say that ‚ÄúI have left-handedness‚Äù, would you? You‚Äôd just say that ‚ÄúI am left-handed‚Äù.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 11. When an autistic person tells you that they are autistic, don‚Äôt say ‚Äúdon‚Äôt you mean a person with autism?‚Äù. The majority of autistic people prefer identity-first language, i.e. ‚Äòautistic person‚Äô. You shouldn‚Äôt need to be reminded that we are a person first, before our autism.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 10. Autism is not all bad. If you could experience autistic joy, you would understand, because it is the most wonderful feeling. Our brains hyper-focus on whatever it is that is making us happy, and we are completely captivated by joy. It is all-encompassing and it is wonderful.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 9. I don‚Äôt ‚Äúlive with autism‚Äù. That makes it sound like a disease. Or something that I carry around. Autism influences every part of me, how I see, understand and interpret the world and how I respond to things around me. Autism IS me. And that‚Äôs okay.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 8. Stop blaming me for miscommunications when communication works two ways. You can‚Äôt expect me to just know what you mean if you don‚Äôt state it clearly and literally. My brain is different to yours. That does not mean my brain is in the wrong. We have to work together.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 7. The idea that someone making eye contact means they are listening is rooted in ableism and is just incorrect. Eye contact can be painful for some autistic people. It can mean that we can‚Äôt focus on what you are saying. It‚Äôs much easier to listen by not staring at your eyes.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 6. Autistic people can get married. We can have romantic relationships. Some of us are asexual, like some non-autistic people are asexual, and that‚Äôs okay too. But we become adults, and that means many of us are in relationships. We can still be autistic too.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 5. Some autistic people can be super social. Not every autistic person is introverted. Not every autistic person prefers their own company. Not every autistic person hates the thought of socialising. Autistic people can have lots of friends.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 4. Autistic people are not all the same. Some of us like trains, and some of us are good at maths. But, some of us like dance and some of us are good at art. The things we find hard are not all the same. Some of us can make eye contact and others can‚Äôt.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 3. We may appear to function well. We may appear to manage life well and not need support. But you don‚Äôt see me when I get home and can‚Äôt get out of bed for days because I am exhausted. You don‚Äôt see how much effort & energy masking takes me, and the emotional toll it has on me.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 2. You laugh at autistic traits like stimming & needing things done a certain way. You think the person is ‚Äúquirky‚Äù. You say you wouldn‚Äôt laugh if they were autistic. But that‚Äôs the thing. You don‚Äôt know who is autistic. I‚Äôm sitting right in front of you, you just can‚Äôt tell.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: But, autism isn‚Äôt a bad thing. I wouldn‚Äôt change it, because then I wouldn‚Äôt be me.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: 1. Autism isn‚Äôt an illness. It is a neurodevelopmental condition. This means different things for different autistic people. For me, autism makes me disabled, because there are significant barriers to navigating everyday life that exist because of my autism.

tweet:
Thoughts are just thoughts.

We can assign meaning to them, which can increase distress. 

But they don‚Äôt all actually mean something.

Much treatment for OCD/anxiety involves letting go of these meanings we create, viewing thoughts as just thoughts, and allowing them to pass. https://t.co/YmpTM80565

Official stats in Northern Ireland are 1 in 22. 

The UK & @Autism need to revise their figures.

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: But it could include not laughing at someone if they don't get the joke or sarcasm, being straightforward when it comes to instructions and requests, and acknowledging that sometimes communication is difficult! /18

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I do a lot to try and adjust to non-autistic communication patterns, and it would be really helpful if non-autistic people could try to make my life easier too. This doesn't mean treating me like a child or as if I'm 'stupid'. /17

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I don't understand how other people's brains just process and filter this information without difficulty. Like, apparently assessing situations in this depth isn't something everyone has to do? Some people can just read the room or understand when someone is joking. /16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Living life with this confusion is exhausting. Every interaction involves my brain spinning and trying to process whether the interaction is sarcastic, a joke or serious. Whether the person has good or poor intentions. Whether there is a hidden agenda. /15

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I am often confused because I can find it hard to understand why people don't see certain things as extremely important, or why people think it's okay to let something go that is wrong. I simply can't. If I think something is unjust, I struggle to let go. /14

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Once I've been in one situation once, or observed how others respond to the situation, I am completely fine. Because I store that in my memory as a formula, and can access it for future interactions. Then the next time I appear to sail through it! /13

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Sometimes I am in a situation and I realise I don't have a script or process of how to respond to the situation I am in. This can really throw me, and is where I feel I "lack common sense". But actually, those social cues which come naturally to others just don't come to me. /12

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Another thing which is completely confusing is people's hidden agendas. If someone does something, I don't tend to read too much into it. But turns out, there is often hidden meanings/messages/agendas behind people's actions that they don't make obvious! /11

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: People are confusing. Often their communication is filled with inconsistencies and contradictions and gosh, do I hate a contradiction. I need things to be clear. Anything unclear and my brain goes into overdrive. Especially when I have to figure out what they mean. /10

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: On a similar topic, people like to hint at things, without stating what they mean. I think this is often a politeness thing. They don't want to ask for what they want, they want me to realise and ask. But it would massively help if they could state outright what they need! /9

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Turns out, they were trying to make an excuse to help me get out of the situation with them and have a bit of a debrief about it. When they explained this to me afterwards, it seemed obvious! That subtle cue went right over my head. /8

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Confusion also occurs when I completely miss subtle cues. The other day I was finding a situation difficult and the person I was with kept asking me if I wanted a tea or coffee. I repeated twice that I don't like hot drinks, and was confused because they knew this! /7

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: But I've learned that people don't always laugh when they're joking. Sometimes they keep a completely straight face. After all, I've also learned it's not "cool" to laugh at your own jokes (why not...if they're funny?) And this can be completely confusing. /6

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Jokes can also go over my head. Sometimes I'm participating in, or observing, a conversation and I'm utterly confused. I'm not always sure if they're bantering, or joking, or if they're serious and arguing! When the people joking laugh, I take it as a joke and laugh too. /5

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I tend to pick up on which individuals are sarcastic by observing their interactions with others and the responses when I take them seriously. Learning this can be really helpful. Except, if I believe they're sarcastic and they're actually serious, this can lead to trouble... /4

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Sarcasm can go right over my head. I struggle to discern if people are being serious or sarcastic. Which can lead to me being told I'm gullible. But wow, can it be complicated. Especially in a work environment, when you're not sure which instructions are serious. /3

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: This confusion is present in many parts of my daily life. Mainly when interacting with other people, which is something which tends to be unavoidable, of course. /2

tweet: Being autistic in this world can result in feeling constantly confused. Let's talk about what that can be like. - a thread. /1

Our world needs to be a safer place for autistic people to be authentically themselves. /17

description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Masking often isn't a choice. It's something we have to do in order to survive. It's not something I can switch on and off. There are certain people I unmask completely freely around, but I don't decide this. My brain just recognises I am safe, and allows me to be me. /16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: This is why so many autistic people go missed. This is why so many teachers say to parents "We don't see the autism at school". Because autistic children, especially autistic girls, mask and when they get home at 4pm, cue the meltdowns. /15

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Imagine it like this. Throughout the day, every second I've suppressed a stim, every second I've withstood a horrible noise, every second I've felt overloaded with demands, and sat there, and dealt with it, adds up. Until when I get home, it explodes. /14

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: To put it simply, I can spend a whole day masking and acting like a 'normal' person, but when I get home, I am so drained I can't even brush my teeth or hold a conversation. /13

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: This doesn't come without a cost. Masking is physically and emotionally draining. At the end of the day, I come in and collapse on my bed and sometimes I physically cannot move. My brain continues to race but I can't articulate myself properly or do the tasks I have to do. /12

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I've masked for most of my life and masking doesn't just stop when one finds out they are autistic. If I didn't mask, I wouldn't be able to do a lot of the things I do or work in a healthcare environment. I simply have to mask, in order to do things I love. /11

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Even little things, like pretending to understand a joke, or sarcasm, because you don't want people to think you're 'stupid' (because my, didn't many kids call me this for not understanding jokes at school...), is masking. /10

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I remember practicing my facial expressions in-front of the mirror and always being aware of the expression on my face. I remember constantly pushing away my distress and my emotions because other kids seemed to cope in the environments I found stressful. /9

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I remember learning that other children didn't want to talk about the books I loved and wanted to talk about constantly, and didn't want to sit and read like I did. I remember learning that I had to stop talking about these things so I wasn't laughed at. /8

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: This didn't always work out very well. Sometimes I would copy what a child had done that was funny, because I wanted people to like me, and I would get told off because I'd applied it to the wrong situation. Or, when I thought Tracy Beaker was a great character to copy... /7

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: This isn't necessarily a conscious thing. I've masked for as long as I can remember. Even as young as five or six, I remember copying other children in my class and also characters on TV so that I acted the right way in certain situations and knew what was expected of me. /6

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Not all autistic people mask. But many do. Many of us learn that it's not safe to be ourselves from a young age. Often this comes from bullying at school, or even adults telling us off for behaving differently. So we begin to mask, so we are safer and don't stick out. /5

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: This can include things like forcing eye contact even when it's painful or uncomfortable, suppressing stims which make it harder to self-regulate, practicing facial expressions in-front of a mirror, learning conversation scripts and withstanding painful sensory experiences. /4

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Autistic masking is, in essence, pretending to be neurotypical in order to fit in. It is suppressing our natural autistic behaviours and responses, and doing our best to appear 'normal'. /3

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Whenever the topic of masking comes up, there is usually the reply, "But doesn't everyone mask to some degree?". And yes, most people do put on a mask at work or when conforming in different situations. However, for autistic people, masking is a lot more than this. /2

tweet: Masking is a survival strategy for many autistic people. Let's talk about it. - a thread. /1

Walking in to my autism assessment aged 16, I was terrified. Not of the prospect of being told I was autistic, but of being told I wasn't.

tweet: Dear mental health professionals. Just because someone experiences suicidal ideation and/or self-harm over a length of time does not mean they have emotionally unstable personality disorder.

name: Emily‚ô°

tweet: I hope that one-day anxiety will loosen the grip it has on me. I hope that one-day I won't have to imagine chains holding me to the ground, but that I will feel grounded, stood on my own two feet and living with just me inside my head, not anxiety too. 15/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I am settled with the idea that I will live with anxiety in tow. It will come everywhere with me, and I don't know if I will ever know the feeling that comes the morning after a storm. I have learned to enjoy things without it suppressing the laughter, but this is rare. 14/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I live with anxiety now. I try not to fight it, because the more that I fight it, the more it bites back. I'd rather live alongside anxiety than fight it constantly. I don't have the energy anymore to do that, and my life is beckoning me. 13/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I tell myself that once this event is over, my anxiety will quieten down. It will hibernate for a while. But no matter how many times I tell myself this, it doesn't seem to ever get quieter. The list of things I'm anxious about get longer by the day. 12/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Once, the feeling of anxiety was unfamiliar to me. I couldn't pinpoint when I was feeling anxious and panic attacks would catch me out of nowhere. I wish the anxiety wasn't so familiar to me now. It follows me everywhere I go. 11/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: When the anxiety is finally released, usually under the safety of my car or my duvet, or in the company of someone I trust, my whole body shakes. Tears fall. I feel my body burning as the emotion is released. I wonder if I'm going to have a heart-attack this time. 10/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I don't just feel anxious in response to events, the anxiety is there before the event, dictating my perception, interpretation and response. I have to suppress it though, because releasing this anxiety gets in the way of me functioning. 9/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Except, is everything okay? Or is there a reason my friend hasn't replied to my text? Has something awful happened? Is she dead? Before I know it, I'm in floods of tears because I know something bad has happened. Five minutes later, I receive a text back. She's fine. 8/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: So you fake it. You imagine chains tying your ankles to the ground so your legs can't bob up and down. You imagine your heart-rate is half the speed that it is and force yourself to take deep breaths to remind yourself everything is okay. 7/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: When your own brain rips apart your self-esteem, telling you that everything you do isn't good enough and that you're letting people down with each action you take, there's little hope of convincing yourself otherwise. 6/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: It's not just physical exhaustion though. The mental exhaustion outweighs it. Sometimes I can barely keep my eyelids open because of how desperately I need an escape from my own mind. The thoughts weigh me down. 5/16

tweet: The storm of anxiety inside me physically hurts. My stomach does somersaults thousands of times a day. My belly aches from the butterflies. My head pounds from the speed of the thoughts smashing against my skull. My feet and hands are weak from the repeated pins and needles. 4/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: My need for reassurance never ends. I get anxious about seeking reassurance. When I'm given it, it calms the torrent of anxiety within me for moments before it returns, demanding more. More and more reassurance. Because it's never quite enough to settle the storm. 3/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I can't trust my own recollection of events because anxiety distorts my memories, always painting me as the bad guy even when constant reassurance from loved ones tells me otherwise. 2/16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Anxiety is not just an emotion for me. It's a daily state of being. It's a feeling that lives within me that I can't quite describe. It never goes away. I don't know what life is like without anxiety as a companion. I don't know what it's like to not be at war with my mind. 1/16

tweet: There we go, that's why I hate instructions. Especially verbal ones. Unfortunately we deal with them every day, and I have a tendency to selectively focus on the ones I fail at. Most of the time, I manage (to my surprise). A bit of support and understanding goes a long way. /18

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Asking why you want me to do something is not me asking why I have to do it, or being reluctant to help, it's simply enabling me to complete the task. I just want to understand, so I can do it. Otherwise, I really, really struggle. /17

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: One very common shared experience for autistic people when it comes to instructions, is a need to understand WHY we have to follow the instruction before being able to carry it out. Except, when we ask why, it comes across as rude. /16

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: @FemboyAspergers Ahh I‚Äôm so frustrated this was one of the main points I wanted to include in this thread LOL

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: My impulse control also isn't great, and this means I can act on an instruction without necessarily thinking of the consequences. Sometimes I just act without thinking, and everything seems to blow up in my face. It's not great. /15

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Therefore, because I forget the rest of them, I'd be told I wasn't paying attention. Believe me, I AM paying attention. Probably harder than everyone else. But my brain simply can't remember an instruction that isn't immediately relevant to the task. I need it written down. /14

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: At school, this was a nightmare. Especially in Design and Technology lessons. Especially Woodwork where I was also battling the sensory nightmare of that classroom. We'd be verbally told instructions, and I would forget them all apart from the first one. /13

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Another thing that can make following instructions very, very difficult is executive functioning skills. I seem to find it impossible to remember more than one instruction at once, so if the instruction comes in stages, I have to write them down. I have learned this. /12

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I want to carry out the task perfectly so I do not disappoint you. I want to do it perfectly, but when my definition of perfect and your definition is different, that can leave me feeling like I can't even begin to act on the instruction because I just don't KNOW what to do. /11

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I am so desperate to not be wrong and not look like a fool for misinterpreting a simple instruction, that I can seek reassurance a lot. Just to check I am doing it right. Because also, I'm a perfectionist. My brain is wired in a way that everything has to be perfect. /10

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: But, even when I know what I should probably do, and usually do this, I have so often been wrong in the past (like with the photocopying) that I doubt and I doubt and I doubt myself until my brain is exhausted. A very simple instruction can cause my brain to be overloaded. /9

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: I don't want to stand there staring at you blankly as I try to process what you have just said to me and consider which of the several ways you want me to respond to your instruction. I guess this is why I'm told I lack common sense. /8

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Not only are most instructions poor, and my brain interprets them very literally, but sometimes the instruction can genuinely be interpreted in multiple different ways. I suppose this adds to them being poor. PLEASE be explicit and straight to the point in your instruction. /7

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: So, in this example with the photocopying, the person assumed I would look at what the photocopy was of and realise I would need at least 10 copies. I guess looking back this was fair enough. 3 would not be adequate. But 3 was what they got. /6

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: If an instruction is given to me, unless I know otherwise based on previous experience and current knowledge, I will take the instruction at its word and process it very literally. This can mean I don't look at the surrounding factors which may affect the instruction. /5

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: For instance, recently I was asked to photocopy "a few" copies of something. I took "a few" to mean 3, because I have grown up with the understanding that few = three. I took this too literally, one of the major problems with understanding instructions for autistic people. /4

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: To begin with, most instructions are pretty poor instructions. A lot of the time this is because the person giving the instruction is neurotypical and just assumes I know what to do with a very vague, very brief instruction. Oh how they assume wrong. /3

name: Emily‚ô°
description: 20 ‚Ä¢ Talking about mental health & autism ‚Ä¢ Autistic ‚Ä¢ Blogger ‚Ä¢ NHS Governor ‚Ä¢ Trustee @AutisticGirls_ ‚Ä¢ #NotAloneTalk ‚Ä¢ https://t.co/5w2cytOQ90
tweet: Being given an instruction instantly doubles my anxiety level. It doesn't matter what it is. It could be really simple. The simple act of my brain registering that an instruction has been given to me and then having to process this is a BIG deal. /2
